1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:08,593
You're listening to: Post-Quantum Cryptography Deadlines: What 2027, 2030 & 2035 Mean for Your Stack.

2
00:00:08,593 --> 00:00:23,798
NSA's CNSA 2.0 sets a 2027 acquisition deadline; NIST deprecates RSA-2048 and ECC P-256 by 2030 and disallows them by 2035.

3
00:00:23,798 --> 00:00:29,134
A plain-English guide to the PQC timeline and what each date actually requires you to do.

4
00:00:29,134 --> 00:00:30,180
Let's get started.

5
00:00:30,180 --> 00:00:34,026
For years, "quantum threat" was a vague future problem.

6
00:00:34,026 --> 00:00:36,454
In 2026 it has dates on it.

7
00:00:36,454 --> 00:00:46,141
NIST's post-quantum standards are final, the NSA has published hard deadlines, and analysts are calling the enterprise transition a $15 billion migration.

8
00:00:46,141 --> 00:00:55,973
If you build or run systems that use cryptography — which is to say, all of them — the timeline has moved from "someday" to a calendar you can plan against.

9
00:00:55,973 --> 00:01:04,987
This is the plain-English version: what 2027, 2030, and 2035 actually mean, and what each date requires you to do.

10
00:01:04,987 --> 00:01:09,879
For the engineering how-to, pair it with my practical PQC migration guide.

11
00:01:09,879 --> 00:01:13,185
Now, let's talk about The two reasons the clock is already ticking.

12
00:01:13,185 --> 00:01:16,370
Before the dates, the two facts that make them urgent:

13
00:01:16,370 --> 00:01:18,413
Harvest-now, decrypt-later.

14
00:01:18,413 --> 00:01:24,783
Adversaries can capture encrypted traffic today and decrypt it once a quantum computer arrives.

15
00:01:24,783 --> 00:01:33,605
So for any data that must stay secret for 5–10+ years, the deadline isn't when quantum computers exist — it's now..

16
00:01:33,605 --> 00:01:36,550
Migrations take 5–15 years.

17
00:01:36,550 --> 00:01:44,362
NIST's own guidance describes the realistic horizon for a full cryptographic transition as five to fifteen years.

18
00:01:44,362 --> 00:01:48,870
The "2035" date is not far away when the work takes that long..

19
00:01:48,870 --> 00:01:53,052
Together these mean the comfortable-sounding deadlines are actually tight.

20
00:01:53,052 --> 00:01:54,627
Moving on to The timeline.

21
00:01:54,627 --> 00:01:56,887
Date, Who sets it, What it means.

22
00:01:56,887 --> 00:02:09,855
Aug 2024, NIST, FIPS 203 (ML-KEM), 204 (ML-DSA), 205 (SLH-DSA) finalized — the standards exist.

23
00:02:09,855 --> 00:02:19,831
Jan 1, 2027, NSA (CNSA 2.0), New US National Security System acquisitions must support PQC.

24
00:02:19,831 --> 00:02:31,298
2030, NIST (IR 8547), RSA-2048 and ECC P-256 deprecated (discouraged, allowed with risk).

25
00:02:31,298 --> 00:02:44,110
2033–2035, NSA / NIST, CNSA 2.0 exclusive for many classes; quantum-vulnerable algorithms disallowed in NIST standards by 2035.

26
00:02:44,110 --> 00:02:46,610
What "2027" requires.

27
00:02:46,610 --> 00:02:56,995
The NSA's CNSA 2.0 suite becomes mandatory for new national-security-system acquisitions from January 1, 2027.

28
00:02:56,995 --> 00:03:02,596
Even if you're not a government contractor, this date matters: it sets the tone for the whole supply chain.

29
00:03:02,596 --> 00:03:13,846
Vendors selling to government must ship PQC, which means the libraries, HSMs, and products you depend on will have quantum-safe options by then — and procurement teams will start asking for them.

30
00:03:13,846 --> 00:03:20,240
If you sell software, "do you support PQC?" becomes a real question on security questionnaires around this date.

31
00:03:20,240 --> 00:03:23,245
What "2030" requires (deprecated).

32
00:03:23,245 --> 00:03:31,153
In NIST's vocabulary, deprecated means an algorithm is still allowed but discouraged, and its use carries acknowledged risk.

33
00:03:31,153 --> 00:03:43,281
By 2030, RSA-2048 and ECC P-256 — the asymmetric workhorses behind most TLS and signatures today — hit this status.

34
00:03:43,281 --> 00:03:54,951
Practically: by 2030 you should have PQC (in hybrid mode) deployed for anything long-lived, and a concrete plan to retire pure-classical asymmetric crypto.

35
00:03:54,951 --> 00:03:59,266
Auditors and frameworks will start flagging deprecated algorithms.

36
00:03:59,266 --> 00:04:02,439
What "2035" requires (disallowed).

37
00:04:02,439 --> 00:04:08,329
Disallowed is the hard stop: the algorithm may no longer be used in compliant systems.

38
00:04:08,329 --> 00:04:13,557
By 2035, quantum-vulnerable algorithms are removed from NIST standards entirely.

39
00:04:13,557 --> 00:04:22,896
If you're still running RSA/ECC for key exchange or signatures in a regulated context at that point, you're out of compliance.

40
00:04:22,896 --> 00:04:32,103
2035 sounds distant, but at a 5–15 year migration horizon, a program that starts in 2026 is on schedule, not early.

41
00:04:32,103 --> 00:04:35,264
Next up: What this means for you, by situation.

42
00:04:35,282 --> 00:04:38,068
You build SaaS / web services.

43
00:04:38,068 --> 00:04:47,599
Plan hybrid TLS (X25519 + ML-KEM) and PQC-capable signing on the 2030 horizon.

44
00:04:47,599 --> 00:04:50,039
Start your crypto inventory now (below).

45
00:04:50,039 --> 00:04:52,635
Long-lived secrets are the urgent part..

46
00:04:52,635 --> 00:04:56,001
You sell software to enterprises/government.

47
00:04:56,001 --> 00:05:00,736
"PQC support" becomes a sales requirement around 2027.

48
00:05:00,736 --> 00:05:04,847
Being early is a differentiator on security questionnaires..

49
00:05:04,847 --> 00:05:12,143
You handle long-confidentiality data (health, finance, legal, government — exactly the kind I've built for).

50
00:05:12,143 --> 00:05:17,924
Harvest-now-decrypt-later makes this your most urgent category regardless of the headline dates..

51
00:05:17,924 --> 00:05:19,570
You're an individual engineer.

52
00:05:19,570 --> 00:05:23,080
PQC fluency is becoming a hiring signal.

53
00:05:23,080 --> 00:05:31,169
Understanding ML-KEM vs ML-DSA and hybrid cryptography is a genuinely scarce, valuable skill..

54
00:05:31,169 --> 00:05:35,568
Let's explore The first concrete step (do this in 2026).

55
00:05:35,568 --> 00:05:37,900
You cannot migrate what you cannot see.

56
00:05:37,900 --> 00:05:55,604
The universal starting move — the one every framework and the NCSC and NIST all agree on — is to build a cryptographic inventory, a Cryptographic Bill of Materials (CBOM): every place you use asymmetric crypto, the algorithm, and how long the data it protects must stay confidential.

57
00:05:55,604 --> 00:06:00,183
That inventory, sorted by data lifetime, is your migration plan.

58
00:06:00,183 --> 00:06:06,578
I walk through building one in Cryptographic Bill of Materials (CBOM): Step 1 of PQC Migration.

59
00:06:06,578 --> 00:06:14,907
The second move is crypto-agility — routing crypto through an abstraction so swapping algorithms is config, not a rewrite.

60
00:06:14,907 --> 00:06:20,292
That's what turns these deadlines from a panic into a schedule, and it's the core of the migration guide.

61
00:06:20,292 --> 00:06:21,866
Now let's look at The takeaway.

62
00:06:21,866 --> 00:06:34,546
The post-quantum transition now has real dates: 2027 (NSA acquisitions), 2030 (RSA/ECC deprecated), 2035 (disallowed).

63
00:06:34,546 --> 00:06:47,984
Because migrations take 5–15 years and "harvest now, decrypt later" is already in play, a program that begins in 2026 with a crypto inventory and an agility layer is exactly on time.

64
00:06:47,984 --> 00:06:59,126
The organizations that treat these as a 2034 problem will be the ones doing it in a panic; the ones that start their CBOM this year will swap algorithms calmly when the deadlines land.

